{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477380","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477380"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:00:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:00:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14339"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14339","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14339"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.88,0.04,0.04,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7034"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54715"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7034","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7034"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14339"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40246"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16738"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44209"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44835"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54715","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54715"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA seven-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parents for a routine check-up. He has a history of congenital asplenia diagnosed at birth. He has no significant medical history and takes penicillin prophylaxis daily. His immunisations are up to date according to the standard childhood schedule. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe parents ask about additional vaccinations their child might need due to his asplenia.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following sets of vaccines is most important for this child specific to his condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rotavirus and varicella vaccines","Pneumococcal, meningococcal, and Haemophilus influenzae type b vaccines","Hepatitis A and hepatitis B vaccines","Measles, mumps, and rubella vaccines","Human papillomavirus and tetanus vaccines"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFor children with asplenia, whether congenital or acquired, vaccination against encapsulated organisms is crucial due to their increased susceptibility to severe infections from these pathogens. The most important additional vaccines for this child are \u003Cstrong\u003Epneumococcal, meningococcal, and Haemophilus influenzae type b (Hib) vaccines\u003C/strong\u003E. These vaccines protect against the primary encapsulated organisms that pose a significant risk to asplenic individuals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERotavirus and varicella vaccines\u003C/strong\u003E are part of the routine childhood schedule. While important, they do not address the specific risks associated with asplenia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis A and hepatitis B vaccines\u003C/strong\u003E are important for general health but are not specifically indicated for asplenia. They are typically part of the routine childhood immunisation schedule.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeasles, mumps, and rubella vaccines\u003C/strong\u003E are crucial components of the routine childhood immunisation schedule but are not specifically indicated for asplenia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHuman papillomavirus and tetanus vaccines\u003C/strong\u003E are important for general health but are not specifically related to the risks associated with asplenia. Tetanus is part of the routine childhood schedule, and HPV vaccination is typically given later in adolescence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor pneumococcal protection in asplenic children, both the 13-valent pneumococcal conjugate vaccine (PCV13) and the 23-valent pneumococcal polysaccharide vaccine (PPSV23) are recommended. The meningococcal vaccine should cover multiple serogroups (A, C, W, Y, and B). The Hib vaccine, while typically completed in infancy, may require a booster in asplenic children if not previously given.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdditionally, annual influenza vaccination is recommended for children with asplenia, as they are at increased risk of severe bacterial infections following influenza. The child\u0027s penicillin prophylaxis is also an important part of managing the risks associated with asplenia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERegular follow-up and education about the risks of overwhelming post-splenectomy infection (OPSI) are crucial for managing children with asplenia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Children with asplenia require vaccination against encapsulated organisms, including Streptococcus pneumoniae, Haemophilus influenzae type b, and Neisseria meningitidis.","Annual influenza vaccination is recommended for children with asplenia due to their increased risk of severe infection.","Pneumococcal conjugate vaccine (13-valent) and pneumococcal polysaccharide vaccine (23-valent) are both important for comprehensive protection against pneumococcal disease in asplenic children."],"references":["Bonanni P, Grazzini M, Niccolai G, Paolini D, Varone O, Bartoloni A, Bartalesi F, Santini MG, Baretti S, Bonito C, Zini P, Mechi MT, Niccolini F, Magistri L, Pulci MB, Boccalini S, Bechini A. Recommended vaccinations for asplenic and hyposplenic adult patients. Hum Vaccin Immunother. 2017 Feb;13(2):359-368. doi: 10.1080/21645515.2017.1264797. PMID: 27929751; PMCID: PMC5328222."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40246"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14339"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40246","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40246"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-09T15:07:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-09T15:08:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7034"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54715"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"39","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/39"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udee1\ufe0f","name":"Immunology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":